The following is more or less a huge note to self on how I have been able to find and adapt to my needs several plugins/scripts. Hope other people might find it useful. Markdown with pandoc-citeproc To use citations for pandoc-citeproc in markdown citekeys are used [@citekey] Creating automatically generated bibliographies with zotero and LaTeX % ----------------------------------------------------------------------- %PREAMBLE \documentclass[a4paper]{article} %Defines the class of the document \usepackage[T1]{fontenc} %Defines the font encoding used %SPECIAL CHARACTERS \usepackage{fontspec} %Used for special characters; requires XeLaTeX or LuaLaTeX %SET PAGE MARGINS (OPTIONAL) \usepackage{geometry} \geometry{ left=20mm, right=20mm, bmargin=20mm, footskip=5mm, } %SET HEADERS (OPTIONAL) \usepackage{fancyhdr} \pagestyle{fancy}  ancyhf{} head{[	hepage]} \lhead{Last update: 	oday} foot {} %LANGUAGE SUPPORT \usepackage[german,french,american]{babel} %Supports typesetting in different languages %BIBLIOGRAPHY \usepackage[autostyle]{csquotes} %A package supporting different quotation styles \usepackage[style=chicago-notes,backend=bibtex8,bibencoding=inputenc,url=false,eprint=false,isbn=false,doi=false,sorting=nyt,journalabbrev=true]{biblatex} %A package implementing bibliographic collections in the document \linespread{1.1} %sets linespread \usepackage{url} \urlstyle{rm} \appto ibsetup{\sloppy} \providecommand{	heendnote}[1]{#1} \hyphenation{evans-ton clem-ens mc-hugh ho-ro-witz} \setlength{\dimen ootins}{9.5in} \setlength{\parindent}{0pt} \setlength{\parskip}{5pt} \protected\def\onethird{{\scriptsizeaisebox{.7ex}{1}% \hspace{-0.1em}aisebox{.2ex}{/}\hspace{-0.03em}3}} 
ewcommand{\cmd}[1]{	exttt{	extbackslash #1}} \usepackage{cmsdocs} \usepackage{hyperref}  ibliography{YOUR-BIB-FILE.bib} %END OF PREAMBLE % -----------------------------------------------------------------------  egin{document} 	itle{A title} \author{Author} \maketitle \abstract{A short summary} 
ocite{*} \printbibliography[notkeyword=nosample,title=References] \end{document} The fundamental command is 
ocite{*} which prompts the generation of a list of all those references which have not been cited, i.e., all those contained in the .bib file. Download the full template here DEVONthink 3 On this forum thread you can find an apple script for DEVONthink to convert markdown to PDF inside DT. I changed the command line options to use also pandoc-citeproc and convert all citations: -- Construct your personal command line options here: do shell script "export PATH=/Library/TeX/texbin:$PATH &amp;&amp; /usr/local/bin/pandoc "" &amp; Path_to_MD &amp; "" -s -o "" &amp; theOutput &amp; "" --filter=/usr/local/bin/pandoc-citeproc --pdf-engine=/Library/TeX/texbin/xelatex --number-sections --bibliography=/PATH/TO/BIBLIOGRAPHY.bib --csl=/PATH/TO/CSL.csl" To allow pandoc commands to work in scripts and applications you need to give the complete path (e.g., --pdf-engine=/Library/TeX/texbin/xelatex, not only --pdf-engine=xelatex). To find them, type which XX in Terminal (i.e., which xelatex) and the Terminal will give you the correct filepath. Note that you have to change the caps lock parts with your personal filepaths. The script is however not enough: you need to add a yaml to the markdown file indicating where the .bib and the .csl are located. --- bibliography: PATH/TO/BIBLIOGRAPHY.bib csl: PATH/TO/CSL.csl --- Hazel A rule for Hazel to convert markdown (or other) to PDF via pandoc-citeproc: here. Application After reading this post, I adapted the content of the command line and created a small application via Apple Automator to convert markdown to PDF via pandoc-citeproc. In Automator open a new file of the ‘Application’ kind: in the list on the left choose ‘Execute shell script’ and make sure to choose /bin/bash for the Shell and ‘as arguments’ for the input. The command is the following: title=$(basename "$@" .md) /usr/local/bin/pandoc -s --filter=/usr/local/bin/pandoc-citeproc --pdf-engine=/Library/TeX/texbin/xelatex --number-sections --bibliography=PATH/TO/BIBLIOGRAPHY.bib --csl=/PATH/TO/CSL.csl -o /PATH/TO/CUSTOMIZED/LOCATION/"$title".pdf "$@" open /PATH/TO/CUSTOMIZED/LOCATION/"$title".pdf As Raphael Kabo did in his application, a display notification comes in handy to know if the script worked or not. Some pandoc / pandoc-citeproc command lines To use pandoc on mac you need the Terminal app:1 everytime you need to convert a file you need to navigate first to the folder where the file is located. To do this just type cd /PATH/TO/FOLDER: the /PATH/TO/FOLDER will automatically appear if you drag and drop the folder in the Terminal window. After pressing enter, you can past or type a command and press enter again for the conversion. A simple conversion from markdown to PDF: pandoc FILENAME.md -o FILENAME.pdf To change input/output format simply change the extension. Files can be converted only to PDF, not from PDF. From markdown to PDF via XeLaTeX: pandoc -s FILENAME.md --pdf-engine=xelatex --bibliography=PATH/TO/BIBLIOGRAPHY.bib --csl=/PATH/TO/CSL. -o FILENAME.pdf To number sections from markdown add --number-sections To auto generate a ToC add --toc To use a specific documents as reference for styling use --reference-doc=TEMPLATE-FILE.extension On how to install pandoc see here. &#8617;
